The recommender system made unsuitable recommendation. 
 Its reasons are as follows: Extracted preferences and dislikes: I prefer well‑written Pop/Adult Contemporary where vocal performance and songwriting take center stage; warm, intimate production that gives space to melody and lyrics; natural‑sounding instruments; tasteful restraint; mixes that prioritize emotional clarity and connection over studio spectacle; good mastering, clear stereo imaging and fidelity when they serve the song. I dislike music that emphasizes technical showmanship at the expense of feel: excessive multi‑tracking and layered guitar walls, claustrophobic dense mixes, and a uniform AOR sheen that buries vocal nuance and songcraft.
Evaluation and decision: Seals & Crofts' material (their hits like "Summer Breeze," "Diamond Girl," etc.) sits squarely in the soft‑pop/folk‑rock/Adult Contemporary tradition: strong, intimate vocal harmonies, straightforward melodic songwriting, and arrangements built around acoustic guitars, piano, light percussion and gentle electric touches. That style naturally favors warm, open mixes that leave space for vocal nuance and lyrical detail — exactly the production and songwriting priorities I value. A "Greatest Hits" compilation of Seals & Crofts is therefore likely to showcase clear lead and harmony vocals, uncluttered arrangements, and the melodic focus I prefer.
By contrast, Out of the Blue (as represented by ELO’s 1977 album of that name and similarly titled progressive/rock works) is known for ambitious, heavily produced arrangements: extensive orchestration, dense layering, multi‑tracking, and studio‑spectacle production. Those are hallmarks I explicitly dislike because they can create crowded mixes and prioritize technical showmanship and sonic grandeur over the intimate vocal and songwriting clarity I seek. The progressive/rock tag also signals more complex, dense arrangements rather than the warm, restrained adult‑contemporary aesthetic I prefer.
Therefore I choose Seals & Crofts' Greatest Hits because its songwriting, vocal focus, natural instrumentation and typically warm, breathable production align much better with my stated preferences, while Out of the Blue’s dense, heavily orchestrated/progressive production conflicts with my dislike of layered, studio‑spectacle recordings that can bury vocal nuance and songcraft.

